New Records: Victor Wembanyama scored a career-high 50 points, setting a new record for the most points in a single game for the San Antonio Spurs. He also made a career-high seven 3-pointers, becoming the first Spurs player to make at least six 3-pointers in three consecutive contests.
Key Match Events: The San Antonio Spurs held a 23-6 run in the third quarter, extending their lead to 108-91 heading into the final stanza. The Washington Wizards mounted a late comeback, cutting the lead to five points with 23.4 seconds left but ultimately fell short.
Pre-Game Insights: The game was tied at halftime, and the Washington Wizards trailed early but outscored the San Antonio Spurs 22-7 over the final five-plus minutes of the first quarter to pull within 32-31 after 12 minutes of play.
Post-Match Reflections: San Antonio Spurs head coach Gregg Popovich praised Victor Wembanyama's performance, calling it a key step in the team's rebuilding process. Wembanyama's career-high 50 points and seven 3-pointers were highlighted as pivotal moments.
Miscellaneous Highlights: The game was played at Frost Bank Center, and the Spurs achieved consecutive wins for just the second time this year, pulling to.500 after 12 games. The Washington Wizards had seven players in double-figure scoring, led by Jordan Poole's season-high 42 points.
